      <hedline>
        <hl1>'My Bum Bill': Horrendously Demeaning?</hl1>
      </hedline>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In the Sept. 12 column called "Coping," Robert Lipsyte's reference to the man struggling to survive on a street corner as "My bum Bill" was horrendously demeaning.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In the Sept. 12 column called "Coping," Robert Lipsyte's reference to the man struggling to survive on a street corner as "My bum Bill" was horrendously demeaning.</p>
        <p>Thousands of individuals are forced to live their lives in filth and poverty, scrounging for food and shelter. The author's colorful anecdote ignores their harsh reality, recklessly perpetuating the false image of persons living on the streets as mildly crazy, harmless characters who are incapable of understanding their circumstances. Then, after recognizing his own ignorance and callousness, Mr. Lipsyte self-centeredly indulges himself, assuming that readers will have sympathy for "how bad" he felt because Bill had lost a leg.</p>
        <p>A column called "Coping" should feature genuine stories about coping in New York City, not mock the suffering of human beings by exploiting an issue about which we have become too numb. BENJAMIN STILP Manhattan</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
